    {
      "id": "ID_NAT_SUBS_001",
      "dimension": "subsidies_incentives",
      "scope": "national",
      "content": "MEMR Regulation No. 2/2024 replaced the prior net-metering framework (MEMR 26/2021). Under the new rule, rooftop solar owners no longer receive credit for surplus exports to the PLN grid — exports are uncompensated. A capacity cap is imposed per PLN distribution area ('kuota') and customer installations must not exceed 100% of contracted power. This materially weakens the rooftop solar economic case vs the prior regime and shifts payback toward self-consumption optimization.",
      "sources": [
        {
          "organization": "MEMR / ESDM",
          "document": "Peraturan Menteri ESDM No. 2 Tahun 2024 tentang Pembangkit Listrik Tenaga Surya Atap",
          "url": "https://jdih.esdm.go.id/",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        },
        {
          "organization": "Institute for Essential Services Reform",
          "document": "Analysis of MEMR 2/2024 impact on rooftop solar economics",
          "url": "https://iesr.or.id/en/",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        }
      ],
      "confidence": "high",
      "last_verified": "2026-04-10",
      "data_points": {
        "net_metering_active": false,
        "export_compensation_pct": 0,
        "self_consumption_cap_pct": 100
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ID_NAT_COST_001",
      "dimension": "cost_economics",
      "scope": "national",
      "content": "Indonesia's utility-scale solar CAPEX ranged from USD 900-1,200/kW in 2023-2024 per IRENA, higher than peer markets due to TKDN (local content) requirements, import logistics across the archipelago, and limited domestic manufacturing scale. Distributed/rooftop CAPEX typically USD 1,000-1,400/kW. Retail tariffs range USD 0.07-0.11/kWh across consumer classes; industrial tariffs (I-3/I-4) around USD 0.085/kWh make self-consumption solar economically viable despite the removal of net metering.",
      "sources": [
        {
          "organization": "IRENA",
          "document": "Renewable Power Generation Costs in 2023",
          "url": "https://www.irena.org/publications/2024/Sep/Renewable-Power-Generation-Costs-in-2023",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        },
        {
          "organization": "PLN",
          "document": "Tarif Tenaga Listrik 2024",
          "url": "https://web.pln.co.id/pelanggan/tarif-tenaga-listrik",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        }
      ],
      "confidence": "high",
      "last_verified": "2026-04-10",
      "data_points": {
        "capex_utility_usd_per_kw_low": 900,
        "capex_utility_usd_per_kw_high": 1200,
        "industrial_tariff_usd_per_kwh": 0.085
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ID_NAT_GRID_001",
      "dimension": "grid_access",
      "scope": "national",
      "content": "PLN operates as the near-monopoly single-buyer grid operator across Indonesia. The country's grid is fragmented into the Java-Bali-Madura interconnected system (~73% of demand), Sumatra system, and 600+ isolated grids on eastern islands. Java-Bali grid is congested with legacy coal oversupply (per RUPTL 2021-2030), creating curtailment risk for new solar. Interconnection for distributed solar under 500 kVA typically takes 90-180 days; utility-scale IPP contracts (PPA) require competitive tender and can take 18-36 months including financial close.",
      "sources": [
        {
          "organization": "PLN",
          "document": "Rencana Usaha Penyediaan Tenaga Listrik (RUPTL) 2021-2030",
          "url": "https://web.pln.co.id/",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        },
        {
          "organization": "IEA",
          "document": "Indonesia Energy Outlook 2022",
          "url": "https://www.iea.org/reports/indonesia-energy-outlook-2022",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        }
      ],
      "confidence": "high",
      "last_verified": "2026-04-10",
      "data_points": {
        "java_bali_share_pct": 73,
        "dg_interconnection_days_min": 90,
        "dg_interconnection_days_max": 180
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ID_NAT_UTIL_001",
      "dimension": "utility_standards",
      "scope": "national",
      "content": "Indonesia targets 23% renewable energy in the primary energy mix by 2025 (National Energy Policy, KEN) and Net Zero Emissions by 2060. There is no mandatory RPS; renewable deployment occurs via PLN auctions, captive/rooftop installations, and IPP tenders under PERPRES 112/2022. JETP (Just Energy Transition Partnership) committed USD 21.6 billion in 2022 across Indonesia Partners' Group (IPG) and Glasgow Financial Alliance for Net Zero (GFANZ), conditioned on an early coal retirement pathway. Indonesia participates in the I-REC Standard for voluntary RECs.",
      "sources": [
        {
          "organization": "Government of Indonesia",
          "document": "Kebijakan Energi Nasional (KEN) / National Energy Policy",
          "url": "https://www.esdm.go.id/",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        },
        {
          "organization": "JETP Indonesia Secretariat",
          "document": "Comprehensive Investment and Policy Plan (CIPP) 2023",
          "url": "https://jetp-id.org/",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        },
        {
          "organization": "I-REC Standard",
          "document": "Indonesia Issuance Body",
          "url": "https://www.irecstandard.org/",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        }
      ],
      "confidence": "high",
      "last_verified": "2026-04-10",
      "data_points": {
        "re_target_2025_pct": 23,
        "jetp_commitment_usd_billion": 21.6,
        "net_zero_year": 2060
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ID_NAT_PUBLIC_001",
      "dimension": "public_comment",
      "scope": "national",
      "content": "Environmental licensing (AMDAL for large projects or UKL-UPL for smaller) is required under Law 32/2009 and Government Regulation 22/2021. Solar projects under 10 MW typically qualify for simplified licensing. Land acquisition is the primary social risk, especially in Java where land prices are high and titles can be contested (adat / customary land). On outer islands (Sulawesi, Kalimantan) land conflicts with indigenous communities and palm concessions are documented risks. Public consultation is legally mandated but implementation varies by region.",
      "sources": [
        {
          "organization": "Ministry of Environment and Forestry (KLHK)",
          "document": "PP 22/2021 on Environmental Protection and Management Implementation",
          "url": "https://www.menlhk.go.id/",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        }
      ],
      "confidence": "high",
      "last_verified": "2026-04-10",
      "data_points": {
        "simplified_licensing_threshold_mw": 10
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "ID_NAT_UNKNOWN_001",
      "dimension": "unknown_unknowns",
      "scope": "national",
      "content": "Key uncertainties specific to Indonesia: (1) MEMR 2/2024's uncompensated export rule could be revised under new administration pressure — developers modeling ≥10yr paybacks face policy-regime risk; (2) TKDN local content thresholds are periodically tightened and inconsistently enforced, distorting CAPEX planning; (3) PLN's coal oversupply on Java-Bali creates structural curtailment risk for new renewables; (4) Nusantara (IKN) new capital development in East Kalimantan is an emerging demand center with unclear grid architecture; (5) Geothermal competes politically with solar for JETP funding allocation.",
      "sources": [
        {
          "organization": "IESR",
          "document": "Indonesia Energy Transition Outlook 2024",
          "url": "https://iesr.or.id/en/pustaka/indonesia-energy-transition-outlook-2024",
          "accessed": "2026-04-10"
        }
      ],
      "confidence": "medium",
      "last_verified": "2026-04-10",
      "data_points": {}
    },
